        <text value="Here,$k$represents the state of the background (arrival and service) processes. Indeed, the state"/>
        <formula id="id29" value="$(k,m,n)$"/>
        <text value=",$n&amp;gt;0$, means that there are$n$customers in the system, system&amp;apos;s mode is$m$, and arrival and service phases are$i$and$j$, but such that"/>
        <formula id="id30" value="$(i-1)M+j=k$"/>
        <text value="; the state"/>
        <formula id="id31" value="$(k,0,0)$"/>
        <text value="means that the system is empty and the arrival phase is$k$. Let us denote by"/>
        <formula id="id32" value="$\bmx{E}$"/>
        <text value="the identity matrix (its size each time will be clear from the context) and let introduce the following transition rate matrices:"/>
        <itemize/>
        <text value="In order to be able to compute time-related characteristics, in addition to transition rate matrices, one needs transition probability matrices, which contain probabilities of possible state change of the background process. Thus, let"/>
        <formula id="id33" value="$\alpha$"/>
        <text value=","/>
        <formula id="id34" value="$\beta$"/>
        <text value=", and"/>
        <formula id="id35" value="$\gamma$"/>
        <text value="denote the matrices of service, phase change, and arrival transition probabilities when the system is in the ``normal&amp;apos;&amp;apos; mode, i."/>
        <text value="e.,"/>
